results.title: Ted: The Kite Man
results.creator_credit: David Withers, Csilla Csongvay and ACMI
results.brief_description: Ted the kite man is a Port Fairy icon. A long time resident, Ted has a kite shop, a big heart, and a contagious philosophy as he encourages kids to explore the winds and the outdoors flying their kites. He and his partner build kites with 3,000 children a year and he believes flying a kite helps you forget all your concerns of the day while participating in this peaceful activity.

results.brief_description:

results.title: Future
results.creator_credit: Garry Dunstan, Pat Hunder and It's About Time
results.brief_description:
Episode number 13 of Series “Not suitable for adults”.
Is there life after puberty? This program examines through a series of comic sketches and original songs, the fears and expectations of teenagers as they anticipate leaving school. The future is seen not only as a time of adventure, but uncertainty, where key decisions must be made. School, life at work and the responsibilities of being an adult are highlighted.

results.title: Adolescence
results.creator_credit: Garry Dunstan, Pat Hunder and It's About Time for SBS Television
results.brief_description:
Episode number 1 of Series “Not suitable for adults”.
A lighthearted exploration of the confusion and uncertainties surrounding adolescence through the eyes of 16 year olds from diverse backgrounds. Introduces the characters Tube, Gull, Curtis, Joey, Rosetta, Angela, Pepper and Gloria. Vignettes address “finding yourself, liking yourself and being your own person”, independence vs. limitations, the “real me”, friendships, peer group pressure and the physical/emotional changes occuring during the early teenage years. Similarly, the pressure of uncertain job prospects, school stresses, youthful dreams and concern for the world’s future.

results.title: Teenage blues
results.creator_credit: Garry Dunstan, Pat Hunder, Australia. Special Broadcasting Service and It's About Time
results.brief_description:
Episode number 7 of Series “Not suitable for adults”.
An episode on boredom, boredom and more boredom. Teenagers, in a set of comic sketches, explore the “nowhere to go, nothing to do syndrome”. Once they take up the challenge of organising the school social, they realise that a creative and positive approach to overcoming boredom can solve the problem.

results.title: Staying Connected
results.creator_credit: Roberto Salvatore, Csilla Csongvay and ACMI
results.brief_description: Meet Stephen Giles, a Caramut local, who now lives and works in the city but remains connected to the town through the Caramut Football Club, which he started playing for when he was 8 years old. He is now a patron of the club, just like his father was, and has helped the community to keep it alive, recognising its importance to the locals. He even puts on the footy boots again to play in the Seniors League.
